<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w> <w lemma="σορός">σορὸς</w> <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <w lemma="τόπος">τόπος</w> <w lemma="εἰμί">ἐστιν</w> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μᾶρκος">Μάρκου</name> <name nymRef="#Αὐρήλιος"><unclear reason="damage">Αὐ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ρηλί</supplied>ου</name>  <lb n="2"/> <name nymRef="#Στατίλιος">Στατιλίου</name> <name nymRef="#Ἀπολλώνιος ">Ἀπολλωνίου</name> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἀπολλώνιος ">Ἀπολλωνίου</name> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <lb n="3"/> <name nymRef="#Μενεσθεύς">Μενεσθαιος</name></persName></persName> <w lemma="εἰς">ἰς</w> <w lemma="ὅς">ἣν</w> <w lemma="κηδεύω"><unclear reason="damage">κ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ηδευθ</supplied><unclear reason="damage">ήσ</unclear>εται</w> <w lemma="αὐτός">αὐτὸς</w> <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w> </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>The sarcophagus and the place belong to Marus Aurelius Statilius Apollonios son of Apollonios son of Menestheus, in which he himself will be buried and [ . . . </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The list was clearly continued on the sarcophagus.It seems probable that the subject was alive at the time of Caracalla's edict, and took the names Marcus and Aurelius on that occasion, but probably had Roman citizenship already (although apparently the father did not). Statilii are known in second century Aphrodisias: cf. <ref type="inscription" n="1634" target="110046.xml"/> (=KRC 28).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
